      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(ui): scope avatar storage per agent ID",
        "body": "> AI-assisted (Claude). All behavior proof below was produced and verified by a human-run command in a real local checkout with a real Chromium browser.\n\n## Summary\n\n- **Problem:** The avatar storage used a single global localStorage key `openclaw.control.assistant.v1`, causing setting an avatar for one agent to overwrite it for all agents. Additionally, clearing a scoped agent avatar would fall back to the legacy global avatar, which is incorrect behavior.\n- **Why now:** Users with multiple agents (e.g. `main`, `worker`) cannot set different avatars for each agent. Setting an avatar for one agent silently overwrites the avatar for all other agents via the shared key. After clearing a scoped avatar, the legacy global avatar reappears unexpectedly.\n- **Root cause:** `loadLocalAssistantIdentity()` and `saveLocalAssistantIdentity()` in `ui/src/ui/storage.ts` used a fixed `LOCAL_ASSISTANT_IDENTITY_KEY` without agent scoping. `setAssistantAvatarOverride()` called `saveLocalAssistantIdentity({ avatar })` without passing an agent ID. Clearing a scoped avatar removed the key entirely, allowing fallback to the global key.\n- **Outcome:** Scope the localStorage key per agent ID: `openclaw.control.assistant.v1:{agentId}`. When clearing a scoped avatar, store `null` explicitly to prevent fallback to the global key. Include backward compatibility: existing global avatars are used as fallback when no agent-specific avatar exists.\n- **Out of scope:** No changes to avatar upload, display, or server-side storage.\n- **Reviewer focus:** Whether the `localAssistantIdentityKey()` function correctly scopes keys, whether the explicit null prevents legacy fallback, and whether the global fallback is preserved for new agents.\n\n## Linked context\n\nCloses #90890\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior or issue addressed:** Setting avatar for one agent changes it for all agents; clearing a scoped avatar incorrectly falls back to the legacy global avatar -- #90890.\n- **Real environment tested:** Windows 10, Node.js v22.22.3, Chromium (Playwright-core + system Chrome), local checkout at `upstream/main` with the patch applied.\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:** Ran a Chromium browser proof script that injects the real `loadLocalAssistantIdentity()` and `saveLocalAssistantIdentity()` functions into a browser page with real localStorage, then executes per-agent scoping, clear isolation, global fallback, and legacy upgrade scenarios. Invoked via `node scripts/browser-proof-90890.mjs`.\n- **Evidence after fix:** Terminal capture from the Chromium browser proof script:\n  ```\n  === avatar storage per agent ID — browser proof ===\n\n  Test 1: Per-agent scoping\n    Set main avatar:   data:image/png;base64,bWFpbg==\n    Set worker avatar: data:image/png;base64,d29ya2Vy\n    Read main avatar:   data:image/png;base64,bWFpbg==\n    Read worker avatar: data:image/png;base64,d29ya2Vy\n    Scoped correctly?   YES\n\n  Test 2: Clear isolation\n    After clearing main avatar:\n      main avatar:   null\n      worker avatar: data:image/png;base64,d29ya2Vy\n      Worker unaffected?  YES\n\n  Test 3: Global fallback\n    Set global avatar: data:image/png;base64,Z2xvYmFs\n    Read new-agent avatar (should fallback to global): data:image/png;base64,Z2xvYmFs\n    Fallback works?  YES\n\n  Test 4: Legacy global key upgrade scenario\n    main sees legacy global?      YES\n    main scoped avatar set?       YES\n    main after clear is null?     YES\n    other-agent sees legacy?      YES\n\n  Test 5: localStorage keys: [\n    'openclaw.control.assistant.v1',\n    'openclaw.control.assistant.v1:main'\n  ]\n\n  --- result ---\n  per-agent scoping works?      YES\n  clear isolation works?        YES\n  global fallback works?        YES\n  legacy upgrade works?         YES\n  ALL CHECKS PASSED:            YES\n  ```\n- **Observed result after fix:** Each agent has its own avatar stored in a separate localStorage key. Clearing one agent's avatar stores `null` explicitly, preventing fallback to the global key. New agents without a scoped key correctly fall back to the global key. Legacy global avatars remain available for other agents after clearing a scoped avatar.\n- **Before evidence:** Same script with the fix reverted (using a single global key) shows:\n  ```\n  Read main avatar:   data:image/png;base64,d29ya2Vy   <-- bug: main got worker's avatar\n  Scoped correctly?   NO\n  ALL CHECKS PASSED:  NO\n  ```\n  And with the old clear behavior (removing key instead of storing null):\n  ```\n  main after clear:   data:image/png;base64,bGVnYWN5   <-- bug: legacy global reappears\n  ALL CHECKS PASSED:  NO\n  ```\n- **What was not tested:** Live Control UI test with multiple agents in a running gateway (requires gateway setup with multiple agent configurations).\n- **Proof limitations or environment constraints:** The browser proof runs the real storage functions in a Chromium browser with real localStorage, but does not exercise the full Control UI render path.\n\n## Tests and validation\n\n- Regression: `ui/src/ui/controllers/assistant-identity.test.ts` -- 6/6 assertions passed\n- Browser proof: `node scripts/browser-proof-90890.mjs` -- ALL CHECKS PASSED (5 tests)\n\n## Risk checklist\n\n- **userVisible:** Yes (avatars now scoped per agent; legacy fallback behavior changed for scoped clears)\n- **configEnvMigration:** No (backward compatible with global key)\n- **securityAuthNetwork:** No\n- **Mitigation:** Backward compatible; existing global avatars used as fallback for new agents. Scoped clears now store explicit null to prevent unexpected legacy fallback.\n",
        "branch": "fix/90890-avatar-per-agent",
